<section xml:id="graphs_vocabulary"
         xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude">
  <title>Vocabulary</title>
  <p>
    <dl>
      <li>
        <title>adjacency list</title>
        <p>
          <idx>
            <h>adjacency list</h>
          </idx> A graph representation where for each vertex we maintain a list of adjacent vertices.</p>
      </li>
      <li>
        <title>adjacency map</title>
        <p>
          <idx>
            <h>adjacency map</h>
          </idx> A graph representation where for each vertex we maintain a map of adjacent vertices.</p>
      </li>
      <li>
        <title>adjacency matrix</title>
        <p>
          <idx>
            <h>adjacency matrix</h>
          </idx> A two-dimensional table indicating whether an edge exists between pairs of vertices.</p>
      </li>
      <li>
        <title>breadth-first search (BFS)</title>
        <p>
          <idx>
            <h>breadth-first search (BFS)</h>
          </idx> A traversal that explores all neighbors at one depth before moving to the next depth.</p>
      </li>
      <li>
        <title>depth-first search (DFS)</title>
        <p>
          <idx>
            <h>depth-first search (DFS)</h>
          </idx> A traversal that follows one path as far as possible before backtracking.</p>
      </li>
      <li>
        <title>Dijkstra's algorithm</title>
        <p>
          <idx>
            <h>Dijkstra's algorithm</h>
          </idx> An algorithm for finding shortest paths from a source vertex in graphs with nonnegative edge weights.</p>
      </li>
      <li>
        <title>directed graph</title>
        <p>
          <idx>
            <h>directed graph</h>
          </idx> A graph whose edges have direction, going from one vertex to another.</p>
      </li>
      <li>
        <title>edges</title>
        <p>
          <idx>
            <h>edges</h>
          </idx> The connections between vertices in a graph.</p>
      </li>
      <li>
        <title>graph</title>
        <p>
          <idx>
            <h>graph</h>
          </idx> A data structure made of vertices and edges that represent relationships.</p>
      </li>
      <li>
        <title>implicit graphs</title>
        <p>
          <idx>
            <h>implicit graphs</h>
          </idx> Graphs where neighbors are generated by rules instead of being stored explicitly.</p>
      </li>
      <li>
        <title>iterative deepening</title>
        <p>
          <idx>
            <h>iterative deepening</h>
          </idx> A search strategy that repeatedly runs depth-limited DFS with increasing depth limits.</p>
      </li>
      <li>
        <title>logical representation (graph)</title>
        <p>
          <idx>
            <h>logical representation (graph)</h>
          </idx> A conceptual model of a graph focused on vertices and edges rather than storage details.</p>
      </li>
      <li>
        <title>loop (graph)</title>
        <p>
          <idx>
            <h>loop (graph)</h>
          </idx> An edge that starts and ends at the same vertex.</p>
      </li>
      <li>
        <title>minimum spanning tree</title>
        <p>
          <idx>
            <h>minimum spanning tree</h>
          </idx> A spanning tree of a weighted graph with the smallest possible total edge weight.</p>
      </li>
      <li>
        <title>nodes (graph)</title>
        <p>
          <idx>
            <h>nodes (graph)</h>
          </idx> Another name for vertices, the points in a graph.</p>
      </li>
      <li>
        <title>parallel edges</title>
        <p>
          <idx>
            <h>parallel edges</h>
          </idx> Multiple edges that connect the same pair of vertices.</p>
      </li>
      <li>
        <title>path</title>
        <p>
          <idx>
            <h>path</h>
          </idx> A sequence of vertices where consecutive vertices are connected by edges.</p>
      </li>
      <li>
        <title>Prim's algorithm</title>
        <p>
          <idx>
            <h>Prim's algorithm</h>
          </idx> A greedy algorithm that builds a minimum spanning tree by repeatedly adding the cheapest connecting edge.</p>
      </li>
      <li>
        <title>search tree</title>
        <p>
          <idx>
            <h>search tree</h>
          </idx> A tree formed by recording how a graph search discovers vertices.</p>
      </li>
      <li>
        <title>simple path</title>
        <p>
          <idx>
            <h>simple path</h>
          </idx> A path that does not repeat vertices.</p>
      </li>
      <li>
        <title>topological sorting</title>
        <p>
          <idx>
            <h>topological sorting</h>
          </idx> A linear ordering of vertices in a directed acyclic graph so each edge points forward in the order.</p>
      </li>
      <li>
        <title>undirected graph</title>
        <p>
          <idx>
            <h>undirected graph</h>
          </idx> A graph whose edges have no direction and can be traversed either way.</p>
      </li>
      <li>
        <title>unweighted graph</title>
        <p>
          <idx>
            <h>unweighted graph</h>
          </idx> A graph where edges are treated equally and do not carry numeric weights.</p>
      </li>
      <li>
        <title>vertices (graph)</title>
        <p>
          <idx>
            <h>vertices (graph)</h>
          </idx> The points or nodes in a graph.</p>
      </li>
      <li>
        <title>weighted graph</title>
        <p>
          <idx>
            <h>weighted graph</h>
          </idx> A graph whose edges have associated numeric weights or costs.</p>
      </li>
    </dl>
  </p>
</section>